In contrast, we observed that NeuralCX effectively leverages both visual and semantic information. When provided with only visual features, the recall@5 for NeuralCX was 7.78 percentage points lower than when the model was provided with both visual and semantic features (Table 3). In particular, the answer embedding provides information about the semantic similarity between Aâ€²superscriptğ´â€²A^{\prime} and Ağ´A, which we hypothesize allows the model to select counterexamples that are semantically distinct from the original example. The strong performance of the Embedding Modelâ€”which bases its predictions solely on answer similarity, and does not model image distanceâ€”also supports this hypothesis. Thus, while visual similarity remains a crucial feature for VQA-CX, our findings demonstrate that in order to achieve peak performance on this task, a model must also leverage semantic information.
